@article{boonstra_conceptualizing_2016,
	title = {Conceptualizing power to study social-ecological interactions},
	volume = {21},
	issn = {1708-3087},
	url = {http://www.jstor.org/stable/26270351},
	abstract = {[ABSTRACT. My aim is to conceptualize power using social science theory and to demonstrate why and how the concept of power can complement resilience studies and other analyses of social-ecological interaction. Social power as a scientific concept refers to the ability to influence both conduct and context. These two dimensions of power (conduct and context) can be observed by differentiating between various sources of power, including, for example, technology or mental power. The relevance of the conceptualization of power presented here is illustrated with the example of fire as a source of social-ecological power. I conclude by discussing how attention to power can help to address issues of social justice and responsibility in social-ecological interactions.]},
	number = {1},
	urldate = {2019-02-12},
	journal = {Ecology and Society},
	author = {Boonstra, Wiebren J.},
	year = {2016},
	keywords = {female, SES, power},
	annote = {I liked how this paper drew on social theory in a much deeper way than any of the other papers on power in sustainability science, SES studies. It hit on the Lukes et al lit, but also on Weber, Latour, Giddens…
The paper was also at times disjointed which probably comes through in my notes on the paper.
The treatment of institutional theory was poor. The only time institutions were mentioned was in the box on “The Grapes of Wrath”. I think the theory development might have been improved by treating structure as institutions and looking the ability of actors to change institutions. They got around this however by talking about human power as both “conduct shaping” and “context shaping”. I took this to mean that conduct shaping was direct power over other others (human and non-human) and context shaping was the ability to influence institutions broadly defined as rules, norms, culture and beliefs. I think this fits into the three faces of power described by Luke’s, where the first face is more directly conduct shaping and the second two are context shaping.
One very useful insight I gained from the paper (though it was not explicitly articulated) is an interesting link between power as exercised through institutions and power as exercised through negotiation. This came out of Boonstra’s discussion: “These conditions include social structures (Merton 1938) and also social events, which refer to specific situated actions and interactions in time and place (Reed 2013).” Social structures constrain and shape human behavior over time whereas social events are distinct moments where a social interaction may have an unexpected outcome (one party may have superior negotiating skills for example). Critically the outcomes of social events can have future impacts I presume on both future actions of actors but maybe even on institutional structures. To link back to the three faces of power, social events and negotiation fit within the first face of power but social structure fits with the 2nd and 3rd That said there is a certain recursiveness to the situation because power structures set up in the 3rd face undermine the ability of less powerful actors to negotiate in the 1st face due to changes in understanding of self-efficacy.
Boonstra’s discussion of the relationship of structure and agency to power is cogent: “agency together with structures and events constitute social power: ‘Power structures [and events] enable and constrain human agency, just as the exercise of power by agents produce and reproduce power structures [and events]’ (Raik, et al. 2008:736)”. ‘Social power’ he argues is made up of both agent-centered and structural power.
In the discussion of the human use of fire as a type of power, the author includes a STS/Latour approach that brings non-humans as actors into discussions of power and social processes. I was unconvinced by how helpful this theoretical framing was to the rest of the work.
The empirical part of the paper is taken from Goudsblom’s work on how the acquisition of new sources of energy based on firepower transformed the ways in which people and nature interrelated. Goudsblom (2001) argues that “there seem to be two types of human behavior that are resilient: changes in behavior that generate and consolidate power (see also Giddens 1984), and behavior that adapts to this generation and consolidation of power (see also Scott 1985, 1990, 2009).”
Boonstra has an interesting conclusion on assigning responsibility for damage in social ecological interactions. In SES its often difficult to assign responsibility for negative outcomes to specific people because it often proved unfeasible to identify causal relations between individual actions and undesirable collective outcomes. But understanding the context shaping rather than explicitly conduct shaping side of power links people at more distant scales if not through direct liability though social connections to negative outcomes. Further incorporating the context shaping notion of power into SES studies helps to overcome the “vulnerability of a complex adaptive systems perspective, or any type of systems thinking” which “explains inequality, fairness, and unsustainability as systemic properties and mechanisms” (e.g. some humans are more responsible than others for the ecological degradation during the ‘anthropocene’.
Relevance to our work: I think it gives a useful way of thinking about negotiation theory as part of winning in the first face of power. But in these “event based” negotiations there are moments where longer-term institutional structures that shape other dimensions of power can be put in place. 
The reliance on historical examples lends further evidence to the need to approach the study of power from a longer perspective in order to understand its more complex dimensions. },
	file = {JSTOR Full Text PDF:/Users/wyatthurt/Zotero/storage/NGGAIUML/Boonstra - 2016 - Conceptualizing power to study social-ecological i.pdf:application/pdf}
}

@article{wittmayer_actor_2017,
	title = {Actor roles in transition: insights from sociological perspectives},
	volume = {24},
	issn = {2210-4224},
	shorttitle = {Actor roles in transition},
	url = {http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2210422416301009},
	doi = {10.1016/j.eist.2016.10.003},
	abstract = {To date, the field of transition research lacks a suitable vocabulary to analyse the (changing) interactions and relations of actors as part of a sustainability transition. This article addresses this knowledge gap by exploring the potential of the concept of ‘roles’ from social interaction research. The role concept is operationalized for transition research to allow the analysis of (changing) roles and relations between actor roles as indicative of changes in the social fabric and shared values, norms and beliefs. It also allows considering the use of roles as a transition governance intervention. This includes creating new roles, breaking down or altering existing ones and explicitly negotiating or purposefully assigning roles, as well as the flexible use of roles as resources.},
	urldate = {2019-02-12},
	journal = {Environmental Innovation and Societal Transitions},
	author = {Wittmayer, Julia M. and Avelino, Flor and van Steenbergen, Frank and Loorbach, Derk},
	month = sep,
	year = {2017},
	keywords = {transformation, transition, Sustainability transformation, sustainability transition, Transitions, Power},
	pages = {45--56},
	annote = {Wittmayer et al. describe how changes in role understandings in a community can indicate changing interactions and relations between actors within a community. Therefore, changes in roles can be indicative of changes in the broader social fabric. They can provide new opportunities for multi-actor collaboration to deal with societal challenges, like implementing sustainability practices, forming an important part of transitions. The article asks the following question: “What is the potential of the concept of roles for describing and understanding the interaction and relations of actors in sustainability transitions and their governance?”
 
The authors begin with a literature overview of transition research. They focus on the key points of convergence of  varying streams within this field and their treatment of actors and agency.  From their review of roles theories, they establish that the concept of roles allows for a more systematic description and analysis of the interaction and relations between actors, which can be made productive for analyzing current and historical transitions.
 
The article provides three main insights for transition research:

A single role always relates to one or more other roles and that a change in one has consequences for the others. This implies two distinct objects of analysis: the single role and a role constellation. The latter term refers to webs of roles, which interact, interrelate and co-evolve with one another. While an analysis of the single role provides insights into its substance, a focus on the role constellation highlights the relations between different roles.
In line with the focus of transition research on change, the authors suggest distinguishing between two temporal aspects of the analysis. Both single roles and role constellations can be analyzed either at a specific point in time as a temporary stabilization or over time focusing on how these change. 
The authors propose to consider the flexible use of roles as a particular form of transition governance intervention, suggesting that roles can be used not only explicitly, but also purposefully in interactions with other actors as acts of transition governance. It is through the creation and use of new roles or by breaking down and altering existing ones that role change prompts changes in collective processes and alters dominant institutional constellations. Therefore, we propose to consider the flexible use of roles as a particular form of transition governance intervention.

Wittmayer et al. illustrate their argument by introducing an ethnographic study in the neighbourhood of Rotterdam-Carnisse. They organized a transition management process of “problem framing, visioning and pathway development and facilitated actual experimentation” to institute alternative, sustainable ideas, practices and social relations in the neighborhood. Their case is based on interviews, participant observation, informal interactions on numerous occasions, document reviews, field-notes and the organisation and facilitation of seven deliberative meetings and six action-oriented meetings in the period from 2010 to 2015.   
 
Paper cites the Fischer and Newig paper AND BUT does a much better job on the topic of actors in sustainability transitions.  Its better theorized than the Fischer and Newig paper. While the paper does not explicitly link the concept of roles to a more theoretical discussion of the way agency embedded in different roles can change structure, the paper clearly wrestles with this anyway. 
 
Relevance to project: Roles, relations, and interactions, all have aspects of power. The paper talk a bit about constructing social roles that place the responsibility of implementing sustainable practices in the hands of citizens rather than institutions. In this context, it is up to the citizen to participate in their communities, actively working toward transitions. This relates to the relationship between power and empowerment. It also discusses the importance of accounting for the social construction of roles, i.e. the powerful vs. the powerless, in manufacturing transitions},
	file = {ScienceDirect Full Text PDF:/Users/wyatthurt/Zotero/storage/ZQI5RCLJ/Wittmayer et al. - 2017 - Actor roles in transition Insights from sociologi.pdf:application/pdf;ScienceDirect Snapshot:/Users/wyatthurt/Zotero/storage/BBUIR2BP/S2210422416301009.html:text/html}
}

@book{gaventa_power_1980,
	address = {Urbana},
	title = {Power and {Powerlessness}: {Quiescence} and {Rebellion} in an {Appalachian} {Valley}},
	isbn = {978-0-252-00772-9},
	shorttitle = {Power and {Powerlessness}},
	language = {eng},
	publisher = {University of Illinois Press},
	author = {Gaventa, John},
	year = {1980},
	note = {HOLLIS number: 990002559020203941},
	keywords = {power, Power},
	annote = {The key question of the book: “Why in an oppressed community where one might intuitively expect upheaval, does one instead find, or appear to find, quiescence?”
This book should be required reading for all sustainability scientists I feel. 
To test the three faces of power argument laid out in Lukes, 1974 (above) in a field setting using a historical approach he focuses on a coal mining town in Appalachia, Clear Fork Valley, between 1890 and the 1980s.
Gaventa argues that a historical approach to studying the three faces of power is the appropriate method to understand the mechanisms undergirding each face. In particular, it will help to overcome the methodological deficiencies of Dahl et al who focus on the first face of power. In contrast the historical method by allowing the researcher to study the mechanisms of power over time that lead to non-participation and non-action can get at the existence and mechanisms of the 2nd and 3rd faces of power. In addition, the moments of rebellion that did take place over the historical period studied and the quelling of collective action by elites lead further insights into the mechanisms of the 3 faces of power and the ways in which they are intertwined.
Rough summary of book: From my own perspective on the book, the first face of power (i.e. more resources to belonging to group A to control group B) seems to be a prerequisite for setting up the 2nd and 3rd In the case of the Clear Fork Valley, the powerful party (A) was the American Association Ltd—a group of British investors who quietly bought up land from the “mountain men” residents during the 1890s before they understood the value of the coal and other minerals underneath. The residents of the county and adjoining counties who worked for the mine slowly lost all of their economic autonomy as all land resources in the area belonged to the coal company. After establishing economic power over the miners by possessing more resources than the minors (in this case mostly natural capital), the coal company worked to both change institutions to further exclude the minors attempts to confront their oppressors. Using the first face of power (resources) they installed their own people in elected positions in the country. Then these people created rules that benefited the mine owners over the workers. They also refused to enforce other rules in law that would have benefited them—setting up the second face of power to benefit the mine owners. Finally, through media and company owned churches, the company used the 3rd face of power to create a culture and belief system that the inequities in the system were natural so workers would not see that they even had reason for grievances.
Through the chapters of the book one of the more interesting points that emerge is the interrelationship between the three faces of power. At one point when the actual power A has over B erodes due to macro-economic changes in the price of coal, the company is able to maintain control because the 2nd and 3rd face are still firmly entrenched in the region. Then when the price of coal goes back up, they reestablish the 1st face of power and then engage again in strengthening the 2nd and 3rd in a continual process. Later in the book the mineworkers strike and a consciousness emerges that the mineworkers have real grievances against the coal company that should be remedied. When this happens the 3rd face of power between the coal company and the mineworkers diminishes. In response, the coal company uses its 1st and 2nd faces of power to rebuild the 3rd face and maintain their position of power. Some of their responses include: manipulating local media, using law enforcement to keep union organizers out, creating fake news and alternative facts, using brute force violence, and using the church to breed distrust on the part of the minors in union values.
Some key points from the books conclusion:
“Once patterns of prevalence had been established within the decision-making arenas, power cold be wielded more readily over the decision-making agenda itself. Since the formative historical moment, conflict over matters of inequality has been contained primarily within the second and third dimensional arenas of power.” (pp. 253).
“the total impact of a power relationship is more than the sum of its parts. Power serves to create power. Powerlessness serves to re-enforce powerlessness. Power relationships, once established, are self-sustaining. Quiescence in the face of inequalities may be understood only in terms of inertia of the situation. For this reason, power in a given community can never be understood simply by observation at a given point in time. Historical investigation must occur to discover whether routines of non-conflict have been shaped, and, if so, how they are maintained.” (pp. 256).
“The dimensions of power say something not only about how quiescence is maintained, but also about the aspects of powerlessness which must be overcome to the development of successful protest”. (pp. 257).
This goes back to the model he presents at the beginning of the book.
Successful protest: 1. Issue and action formulation; 2. Mobilization, locate and overcome barriers to entry in decision making arenas. 3. Mobilize resources for a clearly conceived interest in an open arena.
“What for the powerless are obstacles to be overcome in the raising of issues, for the powerful are mechanisms for maintaining the status quo. Rebellion, to be successful, must both confront power and overcome the accumulated effects of powerlessness.” (pp. 258).
Another important issue raised in the conclusion are levels and social distance. It was even easier for the coal company headquartered in London to exploit the coalminers for generations because they were even more difficult to identify as the source of the coalminers problems.   
The final most general point made in the conclusion is that if democracy is not functioning at the local level in the US, then despite the fact that democracy at the national level seems to represent diverse interests, if the national level is built from local components that actual in sum represent the interests of the powerful than “democracy of the few will continue to be legitimated by a prevailing belief in the apathy of ignorance of the many”. (pp. 260).
“theorists and practitioners of democracy should turn their energies to considering how the power relationships of contemporary society are to be altered if the social and economic depravations of the people within it are to be overcome.” (pp. 261).
Relevance to our project: 
The basis of the 1st face of power is resources. In the book the main resource is natural capital (land and control over minerals) but there are other resources that undergird the 1st face including manufactured capital (the tools needed to exploit the coal) and knowledge capital (the knowledge that the land has value in the first place allowed the company to buy it at rock bottom prices from the more or less subsistence farmers who just felt they could move on to other land).
The 2nd and 3rd faces of power were derived from the 1st face as the coal company used their resources to create institutions which altered the social capital in the community constantly strengthening the social capital of the company and undermining the ability of the miners to build social capital.
I think that this very much supports the idea that a key root of power is ownership over resources. But this just gets at the first face. The 2nd and 3rd faces of power are more complicated and are produced by actors in the system through changes to rules and norms (face 2) and changes to culture and beliefs (face 3).}
}

