	annote = {BC comments on AGH comments:
 

From: Alicia Harley {\textless}agharley@gmail.com{\textgreater} on behalf of Alicia G. Harley {\textless}Alicia\_Harley@hks.harvard.edu{\textgreater}Sent: Tuesday, September 17, 2019 17:39To: Clark, William C. {\textless}william\_clark@hks.harvard.edu{\textgreater}Subject: Re: how deep is incumbency? (entrenched power in science, technology and innovation )
 




Hi Bill;
 
I read through the Stirling paper "How deep is incumbency?” With  a fine-tooth comb which took a while because its very dense. Here is my review which is also in Zotero. While its very dense, its well worth the effort as Stirling addresses many of the “what is the system” questions we have been struggling with and it may serve us well to adopt some of his language. 











BC: I started my comments on your comments below with your purple questions.   Maybe read those first, then come back up here for my secondary comments on your numbered points.  Also note that I have highlighted what seemed important to me with yellow in the text.











 
1. Stirling wants to expand the notion of incumbency from discipline specific like socio-technical incumbency to include any “domain of what might potentially be self to be salient to change in any given feature of the world, extends in principle to the totality of what exists or is variously imaginable around the world.” In other words, he is developing an approach that is balanced across multiple dimensions and perspectives on power and incumbency. “Without unduly redirecting scope for important nuances, disparities and context-specificities in particular settings [action situations].”  











BC: He has some great ideas that have me thinking where I wasn't.  But he also writes as though he lived permanently in the Great London Fog.
BC: His ambitions to be balanced notwithstanding, he pretty much ignores nature (see below).











 
2. Because he wants to be as general as possible he uses the language “social-material pathways”. Is the the language we should adopt? Does "social-material” capture all the flows of resource stocks? I think it does but please comment. 











BC: See my comments on your questions below.











 
3. His introduction is useful in that it highlights the many global challenges related to incumbency: “It is increasingly recognized that the depths and extents of particular kinds of incumbency often form a reason why so many grave worldwide problems remain so persistently unresolved — including inequality, oppression, climate disruption, ecological destruction, toxic pollution and nuclear risks, as well as perennial obscenity and waste of ward. Finding ways to balance incumbent interests on such issues present some of the most pressing political priorities in the contemporary world”. 











BC: Yes, I agree that this is great.   Just see below on my comments that not all stickyness or path dependence is due to power.











 
4. To understand incumbency he argues need tools to understand agency and the "capacity for action”. Stirling goes through a lot of dense theoretical discussion not all of which I found at helpful about how to think about agency but ultimately settles on structuration theory—its neither structure nor agency but both and a struggle between the two (our "yes and" argument). 











BC:  Agree.   You explained it better to me than he did.   But I agree that we were already where he wants to take us with your "yes and."  Thanks.











 
5. He has a figure that is very interesting as it maps different kinds of “socio-material positive-feedback dynamics” on axis that include whether the positive feedback dynamics are oriented more to structure or agency (e.g.  homeostasis vs entrapment) and whether the dynamics are more mechanistic or emergent (e.g. entrenchment vs technological-drift). Finally, he discussed the ways the dynamics are mainly apprehended from interpretive constructivist, to positive analytic to quantitative aggregative (see for example imaginaries as example of constructivist, path dependency as example of positive analytic and economics of scale as quantitative aggregative). SEE FIGURE ATTACHED. What is cool about the figure as it brings together different language to describe socio-material incumbency across a wide range of literatures that treat the phenomenon slightly differently. Structure people probably see incumbency as free from agency, but the figure reminds us that maintaining structure requires its own kind of agency in acts of “status due bias” and “routines”. 











BC:  I can imagine that this may help us get our thoughts in order.   But in my mind it is precisely the sort of "inside baseball" figure that we do NOT want to reproduce in a review that is supposed to speak to engineers and ecologists as well as social studies scholars.   Am I missing something?











 
6. “Socio-Material incumbency is fundamentally about power.” Stirling argues that all of the various definitions of “socio-material positive feedback” have one thing in common which is power which he defines as “different forms and conditions of ‘asymmetrically structuring agency’”. By asymmetric he means the power to create structures that "orient some onward course of events [development pathways] rather than others.”   This definition is confusing, but what he means by it is the power to organize the rules of the system I believe within a ’socio-material’ development pathway. I think all three dimensions of power that we usually talk about can collapse within the definition of “asymmetrically structuring agency” but I am not sure its usually useful to do this except to make the point that all three dimensions of power serve to reenforce socio-material incumbency (which is a useful point). 
 
7. The paper discusses two attributes of gradients of power including intensity and directionality. “First, there are the ’scalar intensities’ of power associated with any given candidate instance of incumbency. Second, there is the ‘vector directionality’ of associated orientations for change at any particular locus of interest.” I believe that both the issues of intensity and directionality help us (BS and AGH) think about using power gradients within development pathways of socio-material incumbency and modeling this as a CAS. The intensity and directionality would I believe imply something about the slop of the attractor domains that should be captured in our figure. 











BC (not, I hope, BS as you have labeled me above): I like the two dimensions of power / incumbency.   I am not sure about translating this into a practical notion of "power gradients" or about slopes... though slopes I can maybe imagine.











 
8. Use of the word focal. Here, the current socio-material pathway is referred to as the “focal socio-material pathway”. I have a few times brought up the possibility of replacing action situation with focal situation. Striling's use of focal pathway suggests that I am not alone in this preference. Thoughts?  Note that Geels ( 2011) also uses focal: "Positive and negative influences from other regimes on the focal regime are an understudied but promising topic."
** In Zotero you will find this paper highly marked up. 











BC:  See below.   I get virtually no hits to "focal" paired with anything relevant.   Why would we replace a term that is well know and used in the field with one that is not?











 
 
9. Finally and perhaps most importantly, the entire thrust of the paper is an argument against the reification of middle range theories like socio-technical regimes and regime incumbency. Stirling feels that the reification of social science theories lead to a tendency to engage in “eagle eye views” and cockpit-ism in policy solutions. He argues that “despite the wealth of evidence and experience qualifying romanticized aspirations to control the inconvenient fact that ’there is no cockpit’ in global governance remains effectively ignored." He feels that rather than an eagle-eyed perspective, we should have a worm-eyed perspective on socio-material regime incumbency where many factors are holding complex and overlapping regime type structures in place views of individual overly determined regime “development pathways” oversimply things. He would almost certainly say this about our \#\#SustSci framework. I don’t think this means we should not use it, but with due acknowledgement that while it is a birds eye view, the real world is clearly more complex. The usefulness of the framework is to help various disparate parts of the field communicate and not as a complete model for how the world works. 










BC:  I found the regime discussion to be very useful.   I think, however, that his effort to connect his very insightful remarks about regimes to his long standing rant against "top down" and "cockpits" does not entirely work.  So lets try to distinguish the strong argument he makes from the rest.   Here are some points of departure from my side:  













I see his helpful perspective on regimes to be something of a mix between STS perspectives (they are socially constructed) and Scott perspectives (top down prescription not only doesn't work, it reinforces power asymmetries) 
His rant on top down and cockpits is fair enough, the SDGs notwithstanding, and seems to me fully in line with Scott.   So is his argument that the pursuit of sustainability is ultimately a political affair.   We should be sure we are saying this emphatically up front.   I think I would even be prepared to introduce his views of incumbency as the ulitimate barrier to sustainability  in our Intro.
One of the other "strong" things I want to take from his paper is his observation that the power distributions of incumbency often run across multiple regimes (or whatever you call them).    This seems to me to be of fundamental importance.   I elaborate in my response to your questions below.
He is not quite consistent in his treatment of regimes.  For instance, at one point he defines them (citing reference 458) as "the dominant way that a societal function is fulfilled."   That is a view I could live with for "energy regimes" "food regimes" etc.    It is also consistent with the description I cite in the draft review of something like "characteristic behaviors" of the variables involved in fullfilling a societal function.   His real objection, which he reiterates, is with reference to "THE regime" (as though it were an autonomous thing, like a carbon atom) rather than a construction driven by our choice of which "societal function" to be interested in, our assessment of "the dominant way" power and other relationships are "structurated" (ugh!) to fulfill that function, etc.   I think that with due deference to STS and Scott we should be able to rescue "regimes" in a useful way for the review that he might even find acceptable.













 
My main questions for you are:


Should we adopt the term “socio-material incumbency” and "socio-material development pathway?? 

BC:  I like the term "incumbancy" and gather it has some standing in social science.   I think it could well complement our discussions of power and transitions.   The one thing we should be more careful than the author on is that not all forces keeping systems in their "regimes" (see below) or pathways are related to power.   Some really are entirely from the natural system (think interglacial climate regimes).   That said, as I seem to recall us arguing in ESPP11, even path dependence or regimes or segregation patterns that have "natural" roots get reenforced by human power and incumbancies.
BC:  I also like how he sums up his view of power (see below).
BC:  On "socio-material X" my view is that we should not adopt this term except perhaps in a footnote.    A couple of reasons.   

Throughout our drafts, we have been trying to reduce the use of jargon, use terms people are familiar with, and focus on big picture issues rather than the nuances of debates on the differences between closely related concepts (e.g. robustness and resilience).   This goes in the wrong direction (neither term gets any hits at the topic level in WoS).    
We are aiming in this review at emphasizing that sustainability must be based on an understanding of the the intertwined character of environment and development, nature and society, etc.   "Socio-material" is only marginally less narrow than the "socio-technical" I have ranted about before.  In both cases, tech is given special consideration as a part of society, and nature is ignored.   Even if one allows that the convoluted argument about "material" could include carbon flows or mercury flows, its hard to imagine any natural scientist believing that it captures "scrublands", and it literally excludes energy.    I believe that our current default for this modifier is "nature-society," which I don't love but which does the job of capturing environment and human development.    Our review of the lit shows the most frequently used (but misleading) term is "socio-ecological."   I do not see how "socio-material" is an improvement.


BC:  On "pathway" I think we are well served by "development" pathway.   Though maybe that is too social-centric, as is "socio-material development pathway.   Maybe we should be talking about something more balanced, like "pathway of nature-society coevolution" or "Anthropocene pathway."   But for the reasons noted above, I don't see his usage as an inclusive improvement for us.


