My Take Overall: I did not find this paper very interesting. Its like political science suddenly realized that future generations exist and decided to review the literature and arguments that SustSci and philosophy have been aware of for a while. They go through a lot of nuance, but nothing really helps us think about HOW to include future generations, they are rather thinking about whether their is a future generation obligation and if so what it looks like-- e.g. is it ok to leave debt to future generations.
That said, it reviews a lot of the literature on goals from philosophy, so if we are trying to cite recent Annual Review papers, than we can cite it. Its just not that well done.
The most interesting parts to me looked at the question of political responsibilities to the future.
"By this, I mean the responsibilities that focus on political institutions and ask what respecting future generations requires in terms of either (a) creating new political institutions and reforming existing ones or (b) respecting future political institutions. One approach is essentially instrumental and is centered on a. It starts by reflecting on what economic and ecological responsibilities one generation has to future generations, and it then argues that current generations should design political institutions so that (consistent with other moral values) they best realize these principles of intergenerational justice. The political responsibilities to the future are thus defined in terms of responsibilities to create and maintain institutions that further intergenerational distributive justice (Caney 2016). A related instrumental approach argues that current generations have political responsibilities to protect the functioning of democratic institutions in the future (Thompson 2010)."
This to me is an argument that should be back up in sustained under social capital. --{\textgreater} so goes with our own argument nicely, but from the political science view.  The question of course for governance and empowerment is how to do this....
 




Key Points

Discussion of whether or not future generations includes those who are not yet citizens... cant vote. Different organizations who advocate for future generations treat this differently. 
Discussion of distant future vs our kids... no conclusion just point not very systematically to some points of the debate. 
Geographical scope: do we care about all future, or just those in our country? 
